column2: 2016    RE:   Water Main Replacement Project #1601098    Dear Neighbor
column3: In coordination with Mayor Rahm Emanuel’s Building a New Chicago infrastructure investment  program
column5: I would like to provide you with information about an  upcoming water main construction project in your neighborhood.      In August
column6: Department of Water Management crews will begin the work to install 2
column7: 306 feet of new  8-inch water main in W. Fillmore Street (Homan-Sacramento) and in S. Troy Street (Fillmore- Roosevelt). The old water main dates back to 1887
column8: and needs to be replaced.     If you would like to receive regular email updates about the progress of the project
column9: please go to  BuildingANewChicago.org to register for the WaterALERT program.  Simply enter your name
column10: email address and the project identification number at the top of this letter.    By signing up for the WaterALERT emails
column11: you will be notified as the project enters each new  construction phase – from our mobilization of equipment onto the site
column12: to the installation of new  pipes
column13: to the final restoration of the street.    When we are working in the street
column14: we may close or limit it to traffic for safety reasons
column15: but you will  always be able to reach your home or business.  Outside of working hours
column16: a travel lane will be left  open for local traffic only.     We will post our work area for “No Parking” as needed during work hours (generally 7am-4pm).   Parking outside of those hours will be allowed
column17: but cars will need to be moved by the start of the  next workday.  We will try to preserve as much parking space as possible.    We know that construction always involves inconveniences and noise. We will do everything  possible to maintain your quality of life throughout these projects
column18: and conducting ourselves as  good and thoughtful neighbors in the course of our presence on your street.     Should you have any questions or concerns
column19: you can either ask the construction foreman during the  project
column20: or call any of the following numbers:       24-Hour City Service and Information Line:  311    24th Ward Office: 773-533-2400    DWM Office of Public Affairs:  312-744-6635      Genwmnot03032016   When we switch over the services from the old main to the new water main
column21: we will interrupt water  service.  We give you 24-hour notice when this is to happen.  However
column22: in the event of an emergency  shutdown during construction
column23: we may not be able to give you prior warning.    Flushing after Your Service Line has been Connected to the New Water Main     Now that your old water main has been replaced and your water service has been connected to the  new water main
column24: it is important to flush your plumbing of any sediment
column26: including  any lead to maintain water quality.      Sediment
column28: including any lead may collect in the aerator screen located at the tip of  your faucets.  These screens should be removed prior to flushing.       (1) Please find the closest available tap (an outside  hose spigot
column29: laundry sink faucet or bathtub) to where  the water comes into the home that is not used for  drinking water. Fully open the cold water tap and let  the water run for at least 5 minutes.  Next flush any  other cold water faucets on that floor for at least 5  minutes.   (2)Move to the next highest floor and repeat.  (3) Move to additional floors in sequence and flush          any taps or faucets for at least 5 minutes.             If you have any questions or concerns about your water quality
column30: or if you would like your water  tested
column31: please call us at 311.  For additional advice and information visit  http://www.epa.gov/il/advice-chicago-residents-about-lead-drinking-water.    Routine Flushing  If your water line has been idle or stagnant for more than 6-hours
column32: it is advised that you flush for at  least 5 minutes to maintain water quality.  This may include flushing the toilet
column33: taking a shower and  doing laundry.      MeterSave  Lastly
column34: if you don’t already have one
column35: I ask you to consider the installation of a water meter in your  home to help you save money on your water bill.   For more information on this free program
column36: go to  www.metersave.org.    Thank you in advance for your patience and cooperation during this important infrastructure  improvement project.          Sincerely

column1: 20272`https://www.cityofchicago.org/content/dam/city/depts/dhr/supp_info/JobSpecifications/OperationConstruction/6000_Mechanical_Engineering_Series/6083_Automotive%20Equipment%20Analyst.pdf`Success`Success`2`2`Not a fillable PDF.`Code:  6083  Operation and Construction Service  Engineering
column2: Designing and Structural Group  Mechanical Engineering Series   Automotive Equipment Analyst       CLASS TITLE:      CHARACTERISTICS OF THE CLASS:  Under supervision
column3: the class performs  entry level work analyzing the City’s automotive equipment needs and  recommends procurement of equipment for the fleet management program;  and performs related duties as required.    ESSENTIAL DUTIES:  Inspects existing automotive equipment and confers  with user departments to determine requirements for new equipment such  as light vehicles
column5: landscaping equipment and boring  machines; conducts research on available equipment to determine  suitability for user departments’ new equipment needs; writes detailed  specifications of less complex new automotive equipment and related  subsystems for use in soliciting bids from vendors; reviews bids from  vendors to ensure compliance with specifications and recommends  awarding contract to lowest bidder with suitable equipment; meets with  user departments
column6: vendors and manufacturers to explain specifications  and resolve problems during the construction of automotive equipment;  inspects new automotive equipment for defects
column7: performance and  compliance to specifications and makes recommendations on acceptance  or necessary modifications; records identification information of  critical characteristics of new automotive equipment
column8: such as part and  serial numbers
column9: for database tracking related to potential  manufacturer warnings or recalls; keeps abreast of standards and  developments in automotive equipment to make appropriate  recommendations for user departments’ purposes; attends vendor  demonstrations with representatives from user departments to research  and review new automotive equipment; reviews invoices for newly  purchased automotive equipment to ensure the accuracy of charges for  equipment received and compliance with contract specifications;  reviews ownership papers for newly acquired automotive equipment to  ensure accuracy and submits papers for proper licensing; assigns  identification numbers to newly acquired automotive equipment and  maintains a database of assigned numbers for tracking purposes.    RELATED DUTIES:  Maintains records of equipment specifications
column11: invoices and related documentation.    MINIMUM QUALIFICATIONS:    Training and Experience.  Graduation from an accredited college or  university with a Bachelor’s degree in Automotive Engineering or a  directly related field of engineering.    Knowledge
column12: Abilities and Skill.  Some knowledge of automotive systems  and subsystems.  Some knowledge of automotive equipment design
column13: operation and maintenance.  Some knowledge of strength of materials.   Some knowledge of equipment procurement procedures.   Code:  6083  Operation and Construction Service  Engineering
column14: Designing and Structural Group  Mechanical Engineering Series   Automotive Equipment Analyst (Cont’d)       CLASS TITLE:      Ability to apply automotive engineering principles to the inspection  and evaluation of equipment.  Ability to calculate the load carrying  capacity of materials.  Ability to draft simple equipment  specifications.    Some skill in the application of modern principles and practices of  automotive engineering.  Some skill in evaluating the condition and  performance of automotive equipment.  Good math skills.  Good research  skills.  Good oral and written communication skills.    Physical Requirements.  Ability to inspect large pieces of machinery.    Working Conditions.  General office environment.  Occasional exposure  to heavy machinery and inclement weather.    Equipment.  Standard office equipment including personal computers.          NOTE: While the list of essential duties is intended to be as inclusive   as possible
column15: there may be other duties which are essential  to particular positions within the class.            June
column16: 2002  City of Chicago  Department of Personnel

Technical skill in making quality photographs.  Skill in  the use of a variety of photographic equipment.  Skill in the  development of film.    Physical Requirements.  Ability to frequently lift and carry  photographic equipment weighing up to seventy-five pounds.      Question: 75lbs. Sounds high ...is that the norm ?    Working Conditions.  Will vary depending on specific work location or  assignment.  Inside:  General office environment or exposure to  unavoidable fumes
column19: noise and dust.  Outside:  Exposure to inclement  weather and extreme temperatures.    Equipment.  Photographic equipment including cameras
column22: and film processors.  Standard office equipment.  Question: Is the type of equipment listed current or is it outdated?   What should we be listing as examples?     NOTE: While the list of essential duties is intended to be as inclusive   as possible
column23: there may be other duties which are essential  to particular positions within the class.

column6: TTY 312/744-1088 www.cityofchicago.org/humanrelations     STANDING ORDER   ON STAFF DECISION-MAKING AUTHORITY   IN COMMISSION CASES   This  standing  order  implements  Commission  Regulation  220.320  as  amended  effective  July  1
column7: 2008.   That regulation provides that the Chair and Commissioner of the Commission on Human Relations may  authorize one or more senior staff of the Commission
column8: either individually or collectively as specified
column9: to  issue orders and render decisions not within the authority of appointed hearing officers or the Board of  Commissioners.  This order authorizes the senior staff to act as follows:   Compliance  Committee.    The  following  senior  staff  titles  shall  serve  ex  officio  on  the  Compliance  Committee:     First Deputy Commissioner    Deputy Commissioner (2)    Director of Human Rights Compliance (2)    Director of Inter-Group Relations    One Advisory Council Director selected as follows:   Unless otherwise directed by the Chair and Commissioner
column10: each Advisory Council Director will serve a  one-year  term  rotating  in  alphabetical  order  of  the  ordinance-authorized  councils  beginning  with  the  African Council Director on January 1
column11: 2009.  Currently authorized councils are the following:                   African affairs  Arab affairs  Asian affairs  Immigrant and refugee affairs  Latino affairs  Lesbian
column13: bisexual and transgender issues  Veterans affairs  Women   Authority.  The Compliance Committee shall have the collective authority to render the following  decisions
column14: by majority vote of the members:     Determinations of whether there is substantial evidence of an ordinance violation (Reg. 220.310)    Approval of settlement agreements (Reg. 230.130(a))    Dismissals  based  on  requests  for  voluntary  withdrawal  of  a  claim  or  complaint  prior  to   commencement of the hearing process (Regs. 210.190 and 230.130(d))     Dismissals for failure to provide information adequate to enable service (Reg. 210.125)     Dismissals due to no action possible against a respondent (Reg. 210.195)    Dismissals for failure to cooperate prior to commencement of the hearing process (Regs 210.127   and 235.210)     Decisions  on  requests  for  review  of  dismissals  entered  by  the  Commission  (i.e.  before   commencement of the hearing process) (Reg. 250.140)      Orders  of  default  for  conduct  occurring  before  commencement  of  the  hearing  process  (Regs.     Orders regarding monetary sanctions for conduct occurring before commencement of the hearing   210.260(a) and 235.310)   process (Section 235.400)     Orders regarding sanctions for failure to participate in a settlement conference (Reg. 230.110)    Decisions on motions to vacate or modify sanctions for conduct occurring before commencement   of the hearing process (Reg. 235.150(d))     Decisions on requests for enforcement of approved settlement agreements (Reg. 230.140)    Decisions  on  requests  for  enforcement  and  sua  sponte  orders  for  enforcement  of  final  orders   based on rulings of the Board of Commissioners. (Reg. 250.220)   Adjudication Supervising Attorneys.  The following senior staff titles have the authority listed below in  their capacities as supervising attorneys in the Adjudication Division of the Commission:     Deputy Commissioner

column16: subject  to  the  oversight  of  the  Deputy  Commissioner for the Adjudication Division:        Decisions on motions to dismiss and sua sponte dismissals for lack of jurisdiction and/or failure   to state a claim on which relief can be granted. column19: and  other  orders  or  decisions  issued  during  the  complaint  filing  and  investigation  processes. (Reg. 210.310)     Protective orders and orders sealing a hearing record. (Regs. 220.410(a)(2) and 240.520)    Signing of subpoenas. (Reg. 220.210)     Decisions  on  objections  to  investigative  orders  and  subpoenas  issued  during  the  investigative   process. column21: and  decisions  whether  to   hold a settlement conference. (Part 100(8) and Reg. 230.110)    Assignment of Hearing Officers.  The following senior staff titles have the individual authority to assign  hearing officers and issue orders commencing the hearing process (Reg. 240.110)

column2: 2016    RE:   Water Main Replacement Project #1601100    Dear Neighbor
column3: In coordination with Mayor Rahm Emanuel’s Building a New Chicago infrastructure investment  program
column5: I would like to provide you with information about an  upcoming water main construction project in your neighborhood.      In early June
column6: Department of Water Management crews will begin the work to install 675 feet of  new 8-inch water main in S. Karlov Avenue
column7: from W. 32nd Street to W. 33rd Street.  The old water  main dates back to 1913
column8: and needs to be replaced.     If you would like to receive regular email updates about the progress of the project
column9: please go to  BuildingANewChicago.org to register for the WaterALERT program.  Simply enter your name
column10: email address and the project identification number at the top of this letter.    By signing up for the WaterALERT emails
column11: you will be notified as the project enters each new  construction phase – from our mobilization of equipment onto the site
column12: to the installation of new  pipes
column13: to the final restoration of the street.    When we are working in the street
column14: we may close or limit it to traffic for safety reasons
column15: but you will  always be able to reach your home or business.  Outside of working hours
column16: a travel lane will be left  open for local traffic only.     We will post our work area for “No Parking” as needed during work hours (generally 7am-4pm).   Parking outside of those hours will be allowed
column17: but cars will need to be moved by the start of the  next workday.  We will try to preserve as much parking space as possible.    We know that construction always involves inconveniences and noise. We will do everything  possible to maintain your quality of life throughout these projects
column18: and conducting ourselves as  good and thoughtful neighbors in the course of our presence on your street.     Should you have any questions or concerns
column19: you can either ask the construction foreman during the  project
column20: or call any of the following numbers:       24-Hour City Service and Information Line:  311    22nd Ward Office: 773-762-1771    DWM Office of Public Affairs:  312-744-6635      Genwmnot03032016   When we switch over the services from the old main to the new water main
column21: we will interrupt water  service.  We give you 24-hour notice when this is to happen.  However
column22: in the event of an emergency  shutdown during construction
column23: we may not be able to give you prior warning.    Flushing after Your Service Line has been Connected to the New Water Main     Now that your old water main has been replaced and your water service has been connected to the  new water main
column24: it is important to flush your plumbing of any sediment
column26: including  any lead to maintain water quality.      Sediment
column28: including any lead may collect in the aerator screen located at the tip of  your faucets.  These screens should be removed prior to flushing.       (1) Please find the closest available tap (an outside  hose spigot
column29: laundry sink faucet or bathtub) to where  the water comes into the home that is not used for  drinking water. Fully open the cold water tap and let  the water run for at least 5 minutes.  Next flush any  other cold water faucets on that floor for at least 5  minutes.   (2)Move to the next highest floor and repeat.  (3) Move to additional floors in sequence and flush          any taps or faucets for at least 5 minutes.             If you have any questions or concerns about your water quality
column30: or if you would like your water  tested
column31: please call us at 311.  For additional advice and information visit  http://www.epa.gov/il/advice-chicago-residents-about-lead-drinking-water.    Routine Flushing  If your water line has been idle or stagnant for more than 6-hours
column32: it is advised that you flush for at  least 5 minutes to maintain water quality.  This may include flushing the toilet
column33: taking a shower and  doing laundry.      MeterSave  Lastly
column34: if you don’t already have one
column35: I ask you to consider the installation of a water meter in your  home to help you save money on your water bill.   For more information on this free program
column36: go to  www.metersave.org.    Thank you in advance for your patience and cooperation during this important infrastructure  improvement project.          Sincerely
